abstract: COLLISION ON THE HUDSON RIVER RAILROAD--A HAND-CAR AND SEVERAL PERSONS THROWN INTO THE RIVER.--The 3 o'clock Express train from Albany and a hand-car containing several persons, came into collision on the Hudson River Railroad, last evening, when a few miles from Poughkeepsie. The hand-car and all it contained were thrown into the river, but fortunately the persons in it received no serious injury.

abstract: FATAL ACCIDENT ON THE ERIE RAILROAD. The Express Train which left New-York at 7 o'clock on Friday morning, met with a severe accident near Cochoeten. The engine ran off the track, on the sleep bank of the Delaware River, and was arrested with its fore wheels impending over the high embankment. The train partially doubled up; the tender was utterly demolished, and the baggage car badly broken.

abstract: FOR EUROPE.--We understand that among the passengers for Europe in the Arctic to-day, are E. C. BENEDICT, Esq., President of the Board of Education of this City, and Dr. BEDFORD of the New-York University. Both gentlemen will be accompanied by their families. Dr. BENEDICT will attend the Convention for th Promotion of Education, to be held in London the last of next month, as a delegate from the body of which he is President.

abstract: The Storm continued during yesterday, and rain was falling heavily at midnight. We hear of more disasters to property on the upper portion of the Island. Two frame cottages in One Hundred and Thirty-third-street were blown to the ground. The dwellings were constructed with all the modern improvements, and just approaching completion for the owners to remove into them on the 1st of May.
